# Cleaned-up version of the important functions

## Find a node by ID

```js
function getNode(id) {
  for (let i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
    if (nodes[i].id === id) return nodes[i];
  }
  return null;
}
```

---

## Physics update

```js
function updatePhysics() {
  // Pairwise attraction between all nodes
  for (let i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
    for (let j = i + 1; j < nodes.length; j++) {
      const dx = nodes[i].x - nodes[j].x;
      const dy = nodes[i].y - nodes[j].y;
      const dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy) || 1;

      const force = config.attraction / (dist * dist);
      const fx = (dx / dist) * force;
      const fy = (dy / dist) * force;

      nodes[i].vx += fx;
      nodes[i].vy += fy;
      nodes[j].vx -= fx;
      nodes[j].vy -= fy;
    }
  }

  // Spring constraints
  for (let i = 0; i < springs.length; i++) {
    const n1 = getNode(springs[i].a);
    const n2 = getNode(springs[i].b);
    if (!n1 || !n2) continue;

    const dx = n2.x - n1.x;
    const dy = n2.y - n1.y;
    const dist = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy) || 1;

    const stretch = dist - springs[i].rest;
    const force = (springs[i].k || config.springCoeff) * stretch;

    n1.vx += (dx / dist) * force;
    n1.vy += (dy / dist) * force;
    n2.vx -= (dx / dist) * force;
    n2.vy -= (dy / dist) * force;
  }

  // Damping + center pull + integrate
  for (let i = 0; i < nodes.length; i++) {
    nodes[i].vx += (400 - nodes[i].x) * config.centerBias;
    nodes[i].vy += (300 - nodes[i].y) * config.centerBias;

    nodes[i].vx *= config.amplification;
    nodes[i].vy *= config.amplification;

    nodes[i].x += nodes[i].vx;
    nodes[i].y += nodes[i].vy;
  }
}
```

### Important note
The “attraction” part uses:

```js
dx = nodeA.x - nodeB.x
fx = (dx / dist) * force
nodeA.vx += fx
nodeB.vx -= fx
```

That mathematically behaves more like a **repulsion** vector if interpreted literally from positions, but because the whole system also has springs and center bias, the visual outcome is a floating structured cluster. The variable name says `attraction`, but the exact sign convention can be a little misleading depending on the coordinate definitions. Functionally: it applies a symmetric inverse-square pair force.

